description.text:
Having rebuilt my Prusa i3 Steel clone to use 10mm X-rods (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1905409), I designed this to use dual Zesty Nimbles (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1843195) on an E3D Chimera / Cyclops. It is designed to work with the X-carriage ends and other parts from that unit.

It is a full set of printed parts and needs a number of bushes, bolts, nuts, magnets, shafts etc. I will try to list these but this is from memory - you may find you require other components, please let me know if you do so that I can update this page.

The main components of this unit include:

  • a two-part X-carriage designed to accept 4x Oilite bushes (10mmID, 14mm OD, 10mm long). Eight M3 x 18 cap screws are required, as well as 8x M3 nuts.
  • an auto-level mount designed for a David Crocker IR auto-level board and attached to the main carriage with an M2 x 20 (IIRC) machine screw and nut.
  • a layer fan duct that is held in place by a number of 3mm x 4mm long rare earth magnets (5 in the duct and 5 in the carraige)
  • a mount for the two Zesty Nimbles and the Chimera / Cyclops. Note that this has some M2.5 captive nuts inside.
  • an optional filament monitor designed to use 2x 24 magnet discs. These printed discs use 24 1mm diameter x 2mm long rare earth magnets inserted alternately N-S-N. A length of clock spring 6mm wide, two hobbed discs, 4 Oilite bushes (3mm ID, 6mm OD, 3mm long) are required as well as a number of M2.5mm machine screw and nuts

The duct, carriage and Main mount were printed in ABS, other parts in PLA.

If there is interest then I will document and publish details of the filament monitor. Please message me here if so.

This part replaces the x axis tensioner on the XYZ Da Vinci 2.0a. The original one broke, twice, while running and hurts the accuracy of the prints and over time will cause premature wear. This is the second upgrade revision and it has done away with the set screw completely.

This part requires a 10-32 tap to be run through the hole in the rear, so that a 3/4 inch long bolt can be inserted to provide the secondary tensioning method that improves the accuracy of the printer and allows you to print faster.

I recommend a nylon socket head cap screw as this works best with the locking prong built into the threaded hole.

Once put in place, tighten the bolt until there is a light resistance but no tighter.

I hope this works for you as well as it has for me (I have about 50 hrs of printing on the new part).

Another update way after implementation. This part has far outlasted the original and its predecessor and going incredibly strong.

Tapping + Hardware

10-32 tap the hole

insert a .75" nylon socket head cap screw into the hole and reassemble the printer in reverse order of disassembly and lightly lighten the bolt until it is touching the y-axis carriage.

description.text:
This is a DeLuxe spool holder for the XYZ Davinci 1.0 Pro 3D Printer. It was designed to be hung from the backside of the printer and allow the filament to enter the printer with as little obstruction as possible to improve on print quality. It will hold spools up to at least 95mm wide and spool diameters up to 20cm.

I've decided to make the spool holder modular so you'll save on filament while printing. Remember to print the arm twice!

Updated version 3.1:

I've redesigned the arms to be more efficient on material use. I've also changed out the dovetail connections between the base and the arms to provide more stability. Detail on spindle and spindle holes has been improved.

Current version 3.2:

Although I was happy with this initial design, I have reworked the holder to accomodate two 608 ball bearings to further eliminate drag and friction. I've also made several dimensional adjustments to accomodate for plastic shrinkage effects and the parts are made to fit tightly.

description.text:
I recommend going with the other enclosure mounts that I made as they are more stable you will need slightly longer M4 screws but otherwise you should be good.

Pretty basic enclosure, I have gone through and test fit these parts and haven't had any problems. I included my cable top cap to pass just the main wires through (the tube may fit too, I just never tried it) and a spool spacer and hub adapter for less rolling resistance.

Things you will need:
at least one sheet of 36x48 inch plexiglass 2.4mm thick
M4 screws,I chose button head to spread the pressure out and not crack the plexi so easily.
M4 T-nuts for 20x20 extrusions
I ordered these in 100 piece lots, they are cheap enough and I would rather have extra than not enough.
I recommend having a hex screw drivers instead of those little keys, makes your life much easier
plexiglass cutter or table saw to make your panels. if you got the saw route like I did be sure you use a blade made for fine cuts and has a lot of teeth. 80+ teeth.
M3 x 35 socket head cap screws to use as hinge pins.
You are going to be cutting this in 36" tall segments, be sure you marking in the right direction before you cut or you will be buying another sheet.
Your are going to need 6 short side panels; 2 11/16, 2 large side panels; 13 1/8 x 36, 2 Doors; 6 1/2 x 36 (this will change depending on how you cut the plexi so measure for yourself before you commit) if you are going to use a table saw for this you can easily bevel the long edges of the panels for a better fit. (if your a wood worker you already know how to do this)

3 short lower panels 3x 13 1/8 to 13 1/4 better to be a little long here
6 short side lower panels 2 11/16 x 2 3/16

there are little brackets to go on the top and bottom to hold the larger plexi in place, as well as holders that wrap around in the middle to keep it against the shorter pieces. You cannot use the wrap around parts on the side with the doors as it would keep them from opening at all, so a made some with no hooks at the end just for that side.

I will be adding more pictures as I progress myself, but its pretty obvious where things will line up.

Tevo Little MOnster

No

0.2 at least 2 walls with 0.4 nozzle

15% with rectilinear, regular honeycomb works well to @ 15-20%

Notes:

the only thing you should really need supports for is the cable pass through and maybe some with the hinges. up to you on the latter. The double sided plexi holders print just fine with no support, if not bump your bridging speed and overlap.

I have most parts set up in pairs (left and right) but in case you mess one up I included singles of the most used parts.

description.text:
WARNING: Overclocking your Raspberry Pi 3 voids all warranties on your Pi. Only overclock it if you're willing to accept the risks and possible loss. To date, my Pi is running without issues.

If you have this case and want to overclock your Raspberry Pi, then a good fan is essential. Unfortunately this case doesn't easily support adding active cooling. My 3D printer came to the rescue. At first, I made it a single part in Sketchup and when I tried to find the best way to orient it for the printer, I decided to split it into 2 parts. I concluded that once printed, I would simply glue the pieces together. To my surprise, the tolerences of the parts are that I didn't even have to glue them!. I now run my Pi overclocked with the following settings:

arm_frequency = 1400
over_voltage = 4
gpu_frequency = 450
*setting may not work for all Pi 3s. Customise these settings specific to your Pi.

Since my memory doesn't have a heat sink, I'm hesitant to tweak memory frequency. The heat sink for memory didn't work with this case. I may add washers under the Pi to allow enough space for a memory heat sink.

Note, the fan wire can be routed in the small semi-circle cutout. The fan should be a 30mm X 30mm by 10mm depth. It is simply pressure fitted.

description.text:
Another neat gear widget I made. The cool thing about this one is that it converts rotational motion 90 degrees at a 1:1 gear ratio. Gears like these are really cool, but are not very practical because its 45-degree pressure angle between gear teeth is pretty high (similar gears and cams don't run well with pressure angles over 30 degrees), not to mention the sliding of the teeth cause friction. As a toy though it works surprisingly well! And it's fun to watch.

A couple notes, I printed it without the little washer additions, So if you turn one of the gears the wrong way the other will pop out. But turning the same gear the other way keeps it in! I quickly threw together a couple press fit washers that should keep it in (it's actually 1/32" larger than the shaft, but for some reason, my printer spits those out as pretty tight press fits). I haven't tried the washers yet so they might not even work, but it's worth a try.

Let me know what you think! :)

description.text:
I know this thing probably won't be universal enough for many, if any, to be able to use, but I wanted to present it to demonstrate how useful having a 3D printer can be and hopefully spark some ideas in others. For most, please enjoy the story...

My wife purchased a raft for us to pull behind our boat but it didn't come with an inflator, you had to purchase that separately (of course). I reminded her that we already have two other inflators that came with the blowup mattresses we have (why we have two, I don't know), so I was sure we could use one of them. Unfortunately (and the reason why this thing won't be helpful to anyone) the adapters didn't fit the raft blow up port. Thankfully, I was able to quickly measure, design, and print an adapter that fit the inflator and the raft port.

Needless to say, I'm always looking for reasons to justify having the 3D printer around. This is one example of a few opportunities that have come up so far. I will post other, hopefully more useful, things as I print them out and make sure they work.

This is a mini-shuttle styled after the one on the old Starcom tv show. It is compatible with my Magnet man design, rover design, and toy space station design.

To assemble print all parts (8x the peg) and press fit together. Pegs may need to be resized slightly depending on your printer tolerances.

The lid and nose are designed to have compatible holes to press fit in Primal Horizon Magnets (1/8" x 1/16") (I found mine using amazon). The bottom of the core is designed to press-fit Hillman brand ceramic block magnets part no. 542000 (I found mine at my local hardware store).

If you want to make a docking part for the toy space station also print out IntThread.stl and then cut to size and super glue a piece of steal in the recess (I used 1/2" weld stock cut to length that I found at my local hardware store).

This is an addition to this frame-mounted spool holder I designed last year:

This prints as 6 pieces:

  • Rod
  • 2 spacer endcaps
  • 1...bushing? I didn't know what to call it. The inner part around the rod.
  • 2 actual holder pieces

The rod has a print-in-place truss rod designed. It feels strong, so I think the truss rod helped. The slots in the rod allow it to fit snugly into the old spool holder rod slots. The "bushing" was designed this way to save on material and to also positively contribute to the rigidity of the rod. Prints vertically with no support.

The holder pieces should allow you to center the spool. They are designed to hold a standard 1 kg spool (or what has been standard across the spools I have purchased) with extra spacing for free spinning of the spool. It should hold a spool with anything above 53.5 mm diameter hole. Prints without support if you stand it on the outer face.

description.text:
This is a remix of the EAB utility blade.

Motivation:
I found that the original EAB when printed in PLA would have the locking mechanism snap off very easily. There was also no way to flush mount the screw and retaining nut.

Overview of changes:
Re-designed the locking mechanism for PLA. (Moved it over and reinforced the piece)
Modified the tolerances around the blade swivel for a 0.4mm hotend.
Reduced size of pocket clip.
Added inset holes for M3 screw and M3 nut.
Chamfered the blade cover.

Two Updates!
1) I added little tabs on the flipping part of the knife so that it is easier to grab.
2) I wasn't happy with the locking mechanism in PLA so I remodeled it to have a metal insert instead. I know, I know. It now no longer works right off the build plate, but after using the original version for months, the plastic just didn't feel safe. Also, the metal/plastic looks really slick.

title: Customizable PLA/ABS flexible timing belt tool

description.text:
Since my printer is not capable of printing flexible material, I was looking for a solution where I could use PLA/ABS to create something that could function as timing belt. The closest thing I could find was the Moon Rover by Emmett, which works great, but wasn't exactly what I was looking for. Therefore I decided to create a little tool (for Solidworks) to create custom flexible PLA/ABS timing belts based on the same principle.
video

I haven't had the chance to test the print thoroughly, but already have encountered a few disadvantages compared to real timing belts:

  • The tensile force these belts can handle are not too high.
  • The belts tend to deform a little over time, making it less elastic (haven't had the chance to fully test this).
  • The belts are less flexible than real belts.

Nevertheless, I still think there are plenty of applications that suit these, rather cheap, belts!

The tool can only be used in Solidworks, since it basically is a Solidworks sketch with a bunch of global variables that can be adjusted. There two Solidworks files: Belt_tool.sldprt (to create the timing belt) and Pulley_tool.sldprt (surprisingly, to create the timing pulley's that come with it.).

Steps to create the pulleys:
  1. Open Pulley_tool.sldprt
  2. Tools -> Equations
  3. Change values of 'numberOfTeeth', 'pulleyThickness' and 'shaftR' to the prefered values
  4. OK
  5. Save to stl or different .sldprt

The radius of the entire pulley (teeth not counted) can be found behind the parameter 'effectiveR'.

Steps to create the belt:
  1. Open Belt_tool.sldprt
  2. Tools -> Equations
  3. Change values of 'materialthickness', 'beltWidth' and 'cellHeight' to the prefered values
  4. Then you'll have two options:
    • OPTION 1: Adjust 'preferedR' to the prefered radius of the total belt when round. Check 'ClosestR' to determine whether the used radius is close enough to this value
    • OPTION 2: Enter the number teeth of the first and second pulley behind 'numberOfTeethPulley1/2' and enter the distance of the centers of these pulleys behind centerDistance
  5. OK
  6. Save to stl or different .sldprt
Parameters explained:
  • numberOfTeeth: Number of teeth in your pulley
  • pulleyThickness: Thickness of the pulley
  • shaftR: radius of the hole in the middle of the pulley
  • materialThickness: The thickness of the belt, preferably change this to the smallest layer width your printer can reach
  • beltWidth: width of the belt
  • cellHeight: distance between inner and outer radius

title: Desktop rock tumbler / ball mill / rotary mixer

description.text:
Updated with some gcode that I put together. It prints a cap and body pretty slow and with 0.1 mm layers at the threaded bits. I don't use a cooling fan and the parts came out really well. I had to cut a little off the top to make it flat where it curled slightly. Weighs ~52.5g with PLA. I am not a doctor, results may vary.

https://youtu.be/MB1M9SMeyfQ

This has been a fun little project to work on. It actually functions, unlike my previous ball mill design. The parts need to come out really, really good though for it not to leak. Designed around a motor that I got from an old printer. It already had the pictured gear set on there so I glued the drive gear on with CA. Initially I had use internal threads for the cap, but that leaked like a sieve. Changed it to external threads on the body and it doesn't leak from the cap at least. If your printer is tuned and properly extruding, this shouldn't be an issue. Just watch for first layer porn to happen.

I've just noticed that the holder is perfect for a "finest nutrition" vitamin D3 bottle of 220 count. I think it might be possible to use that bottle and a printed Ninjaflex belt. More research required. I have 50g of ninjaflex waiting for some new found purpose.

Tested with Maker Geeks PLA, but something harder and more abrade resistant like perhaps nylon or polycarbonate would be better.

Thanks go out to ArcMatt for his feedback and criticism, despite self proclaimed negativity :P 

Note: The thread tolerances are only 0.2, if your printer is not very dimensionaly accurate then I would suggest scaling just slightly.

Printer:

Dildahmetron

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

25%

Notes:

The drive gear needs to be printed at the same time as anything else it's height. The mill body desperately needs a very tight, squished first layer, like most other prints. Use three shells for the cap and mill body files. Either than that, the orientations are pretty obvious. Holder prints on it's back, as does the motor mount.

I recommend running some CA glue along anything that might not hold water such as the beginning and end line up the side. Also, glue the stabilizer onto the motor mount to make sure it doesn't tip over during use. You might even want to epoxy coat the inside of it for serious use. That remains untested as of yet.
Fusion 360, like always. Used the python script add-on for making the spur gears.

title: XT60 connector support for Anet A8 heatbed

description.text:
After some long run print, my Anet A8 headbed connector started to melt.
So I wanted to change it to XT60 connectors which are more reliable.

I didn't want to solder directly the wires to the headbed due to the possible wire stress break and with a connector it's easier to perform maintenance on the printer.

It was printed in PLA. After 4 months of use and many long prints with PLA, ABS and PETG, I noticed a small bending (less than 1mm) at the middle of the support. So maybe for more strength, it could be better to print it in ABS or PETG.

To fix in to the bed I made small aluminum brackets (35x15mm). See picture for details

Be careful to the final height in order not to hit the Y stepper motor.

Great idea! Did you solder the socket to the existing pins on the heated bed, or to the traces on the circuit board?
One suggestion -- swap the male and female sides of the XT60 so there aren't exposed pins carrying current when unplugged from the bed. I realize the pins are recessed a little, but it would be easy to accidentally short the pins when they're at the end of a loose wire like that.

title: Anet A8 Extruder Fan Caddy + Aus3D Sensor Mount

description.text:
This is yet another solution to the Anet A8's well-known filament loading problem. You know, the problem where loading filament is like performing surgery blindfolded.

This fan design replaces the heat sink with a "holster" that accepts a fan "caddy," into which you can insert your 40mm fan. The fan slides in and out easily by holding the small handle so that you can see inside the extruder.

I designed this to fit my Noiseblocker NB BlackSilentFan XM2 40mm fan, but other 40mm fans will likely fit (such as the Anet A8 stock fan, though not tested).

The bottom edge of the holster piece has two protruding slots designed to mount the Aus3D IR Z stop sensor (use M3 screws and nuts). In my setup, the sensor board came too close to the semicircle blower fan nozzle, so I added three M3 washers between the mounts and the board to space it just right. I could do a better job on this feature in the future.

Two fan caddies are provided here: one with and another without "bunny ears." I experienced a little curling in my print because of the narrowness of the outline. You may elect to use a raft instead, in which case don't use the bunny ears version.

description.text:
A flower pot cane support for up to 4 canes, suitable for a 5” ( or bigger ) pot. The idea is that the cane support is placed first in the pot then the soil and plant on top. The weight of the soil keeps the cane support stable. The support is suitable for canes up to 12mm dia. Sizes of the cane support are given in one of the photos.

The design was based on a single cane support that I saw in a garden center a few years ago. Last year I had the need for cane support but finished up using string - not very good. So this year I designed the above, and it works great. Since the prototype I have thinned down the walls etc. Thin flexible canes can be used which would enable them to be pulled together at the top.

Simple design Requirement
The design need is that you want to support tall plants to be grown in a 5" pot. Additional
Use the soil in the pot as balast to hold the cane support stable.

A simple design of 3 parts 1) A thin base plate, with holes for drainage.
2) 4 tubes to hold the canes.
and
3) Support webs to strengthen the tube attachment to the base and each tube.

I used PLA the make the initial support, but because of the hostile conditions I have also used PETG.
Obviously canes, crocks, soil and a plant are required to get a finished product

description.text:
This bridgepile can be combined with the floor plates i created.

Check my other designs :-)

Tetrarhons are four rhombic dodecahedrons joined at their faces. Among the 28 pieces there are 14 nonplanar ones, which can't be turned to get all four parts touching the ground. You can get different constructions with these pieces, if you place corners with three edges at the bottom (e.g. a tetrahedron) or corners with four edges at the bottom (e.g. a L-shaped roof) or rhombs at the bottom (e.g kind of boxes).

In my program the rhombic dodecahedrons were represented by cubes in a cubic lattice. Therefore I must turn the pieces around to get at least one rhomb in the x-y-plane. Then I printed the pieces with ABS-filament (0.4mm nozzle) and removed the support material. Since the faces got an inset of 0.2mm little differences in size doesn't matter that much.
